# 7. How Java Executes Lambda (Internal Logic)

This is one of the most important interview concepts.

Suppose

```java
interface Calculator{

    int add(int a,int b);

}
```

Lambda

```java
Calculator c=(a,b)->a+b;
```

Many beginners think:

> "Where is the class?"

The compiler creates it behind the scenes.

Imagine Java creates something like:

```java
class TempCalculator implements Calculator{

    @Override
    public int add(int a,int b){

        return a+b;

    }

}
```

Then it creates the object:

```java
Calculator c=new TempCalculator();
```

This generated implementation is hidden from you, which is why lambda syntax is so concise.

---

# 8. Memory Representation

Imagine

```java
Calculator c=(a,b)->a+b;
```

Memory looks like

```
STACK

c

↓

reference

--------------------

HEAP

Generated Lambda Object

↓

add()

↓

return a+b
```

Just like normal objects, the lambda implementation is represented by an object at runtime.

