# 1. What is Lambda?

## Definition (Interview)

A **Lambda Expression** is a concise way to provide the implementation of the **single abstract method** of a **Functional Interface**.

In simple words,

> A Lambda is an **anonymous function (method without a name)** that lets us write the implementation of a functional interface without creating a separate class.

---

## Before Java 8

Suppose we have:

```java
interface Greeting {
    void sayHello();
}
```

To implement it:

```java
class GreetingImpl implements Greeting {

    @Override
    public void sayHello() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
}
```

Create object

```java
Greeting g = new GreetingImpl();
g.sayHello();
```

Output

```
Hello
```

---

## Java 8

```java
Greeting g = () -> System.out.println("Hello");

g.sayHello();
```

Output

```
Hello
```

Notice how much code was removed.

---

# Real Meaning

A Lambda is **not a method call**.

It is **only the implementation of a method**.

Think of it like this:

```text
Interface

↓

Method Declaration

↓

Lambda

↓

Method Implementation
```

---

# 2. Why Lambda?

This is one of the most asked interview questions.

---

## Problem Before Java 8

Suppose we wanted to compare two numbers.

We had to create

```
Interface

↓

Class

↓

Override Method

↓

Object

↓

Call Method
```

Even for one line of code.

Example

```java
Comparator<Integer> c = new Comparator<Integer>() {

    @Override
    public int compare(Integer a, Integer b) {

        return a - b;

    }

};
```

Very lengthy.

---

## Java 8

```java
Comparator<Integer> c = (a, b) -> a - b;
```

Same work.

Only one line.

---

## Advantages of Lambda

### 1. Less Code

Old Java

```java
new Runnable() {

    @Override
    public void run() {

        System.out.println("Running");

    }

};
```

Lambda

```java
() -> System.out.println("Running");
```

---

### 2. Easy to Read

Less boilerplate.

Cleaner code.

---

### 3. Supports Functional Programming

Instead of passing objects,

you pass behavior.

Example

```java
list.forEach(name -> System.out.println(name));
```

---

### 4. Used Everywhere

* Stream API
* Collections
* Sorting
* Threading
* Event Handling

---

# Interview Answer

**Why was Lambda introduced?**

> Lambda Expressions were introduced to reduce boilerplate code, improve readability, support functional programming, and simplify the implementation of functional interfaces.

