# 4. Functional Interface

This is the heart of Lambda.

Without Functional Interface,

Lambda cannot exist.

---

## Definition

A Functional Interface is an interface that contains **exactly one abstract method**.

Example

```java
interface Calculator {

    int add(int a, int b);

}
```

Only one abstract method.

So

Lambda works.

```java
Calculator c = (a, b) -> a + b;
```

---

## Not Functional Interface

```java
interface Test {

    void print();

    void show();

}
```

Now Lambda

```java
Test t = () -> System.out.println("Hello");
```

Compilation Error.

---

## Why?

Java gets confused.

```
Should I implement

print()

OR

show()?
```

No answer.

Hence,

only one abstract method.

---

## @FunctionalInterface

Java provides an annotation.

```java
@FunctionalInterface
interface Calculator {

    int add(int a, int b);

}
```

---

If someone later adds another abstract method

```java
void subtract();
```

Compiler immediately gives an error.

This protects the interface.

---

# Interview Answer

**What is Functional Interface?**

> A Functional Interface is an interface with exactly one abstract method. Lambda expressions provide the implementation for that single abstract method.

